msgstr ""

#: ../../_sources/GUIandEventDrivenProgramming/03_widgets.rst:103
msgid ""
"After importing the Tkinter modules as shown above, the first thing you "
"need to do is create a window for your application. This is done by "
"creating a ``Tk`` object:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../_sources/GUIandEventDrivenProgramming/03_widgets.rst:107
msgid "application_window = tk.Tk()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../_sources/GUIandEventDrivenProgramming/03_widgets.rst:111
msgid ""
"Then you create widgets and add them to the window's widget hierarchy. "
"For example, to create a button you would call either the ``tk`` or the "
"``tkk`` ``Button`` method and send the ``application_window`` as the "
"first argument:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../_sources/GUIandEventDrivenProgramming/03_widgets.rst:116
msgid ""
"cmd_button = tk.Button(application_window, text=\"Example\")\n"
"# or\n"
"cmd_button = tkk.Button(application_window, text=\"Example\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../_sources/GUIandEventDrivenProgramming/03_widgets.rst:122
msgid ""
"The parameters needed to correctly create each widget varies, so you will"
" need to refer to the Python documentation for each specific widget type."
" As of fall 2016, the most current version of the Tkinter module is "
"version 25 and its documentation can be found at "
"https://docs.python.org/3/library/tk.html"
msgstr ""

#: ../../_sources/GUIandEventDrivenProgramming/03_widgets.rst:127
msgid ""
"Notice that in the above code, ``Tk()`` and ``Button()`` are both "
"capitalized. By convention, this indicates that the window and the button"
" are instances of a Python class. The Tkinter module is entirely object-"
"oriented and makes extensive use of object-oriented language features."
msgstr ""

